capybara in nightmare land
==========================
Platform : KUBSTU CTF
Category : Steganography
Points   : 100
Flag     : KubSTU{th3_n1ghtm4r3_1s_ov3r_530}

------------------------------------------------------------------
THE CHALLENGE
------------------------------------------------------------------

We were given a file called capybara_nightmare.jpg and told that
"not everything is as it seems." We needed to find a hidden flag.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 -- FILE IDENTIFICATION
------------------------------------------------------------------

First move with any unknown file: confirm what it actually is.

    file capybara_nightmare.jpg

Output: JPEG image data, standard format.

Nothing unusual on the surface. It opens as a normal image. The
challenge is telling us something is hidden inside it, not that
the file format itself is broken.

Remember: the file command reads the magic bytes at the start of
a file, not the extension. A .jpg renamed to .txt would still
return "JPEG image data." If the output matches the extension,
the container is legitimate -- the hidden content is buried
somewhere inside it.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2 -- STRINGS ANALYSIS
------------------------------------------------------------------

Running strings on an image file pulls out any readable text
sequences embedded in the binary. This catches things hidden
after the actual image data ends.

    strings capybara_nightmare.jpg

Near the end of the output we found a suspicious Base64 string
appearing after the FF D9 marker. FF D9 is the JPEG end-of-file
marker. Anything after it is invisible to image viewers but
fully present in the file bytes.

Remember: JPEG files end at FF D9. Image viewers stop reading
there. But the operating system stores every byte in the file,
including anything appended after that marker. This is one of
the oldest and simplest steganography tricks -- just append data
after the EOF marker of a valid image. strings will always catch
readable text hiding there.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 3 -- BINWALK EXTRACTION
------------------------------------------------------------------

The Base64 string suggested embedded data. We ran binwalk to
scan for nested file signatures inside the JPEG.

    binwalk capybara_nightmare.jpg

binwalk found a ZIP archive signature starting at a specific
offset inside the file. We extracted it:

    binwalk -e capybara_nightmare.jpg

This created an output folder containing the hidden ZIP archive.

Remember: binwalk scans a file for known magic byte sequences
of hundreds of file formats and reports every offset where it
finds one. The -e flag automatically extracts everything it
finds. After extraction, check the output folder -- binwalk
names it with an underscore prefix matching the original
filename.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 4 -- DECRYPT THE ZIP
------------------------------------------------------------------

The extracted ZIP was password-protected. The challenge
description mentioned the number 530 prominently. We tried it
as the password.

    unzip _capybara_nightmare.jpg.extracted/archive.zip

Password prompt: 530

The archive unlocked and contained a file called image_94a08a.png.

Remember: in CTF steganography challenges, the password for a
protected archive is almost always hidden in the challenge
description itself -- as a number, a word, or something visible
in the image. Read the description carefully before trying
wordlists. The hint is usually right there.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 5 -- CHECK METADATA OF EXTRACTED FILE
------------------------------------------------------------------

We opened image_94a08a.png. It looked like a normal image. We
checked its metadata:

    exiftool image_94a08a.png

The Comment field contained the flag in plaintext.

Remember: after extracting a hidden file from a steganography
challenge, always run exiftool on it before anything else.
Metadata fields like Comment, Artist, Description, and
UserComment are extremely common hiding spots and exiftool
reads all of them in one command.

------------------------------------------------------------------
FULL COMMAND SEQUENCE
------------------------------------------------------------------

    file capybara_nightmare.jpg
    strings capybara_nightmare.jpg
    binwalk capybara_nightmare.jpg
    binwalk -e capybara_nightmare.jpg
    unzip _capybara_nightmare.jpg.extracted/archive.zip
    exiftool image_94a08a.png

